â€ƒâ€ƒ Shay Vargaftik â€ƒâ€ƒ Ran Ben Basat â€ƒâ€ƒ Amit Portnoy â€ƒâ€ƒ Gal Mendelson â€ƒâ€ƒ Yaniv Ben-Itzhak â€ƒâ€ƒ Michael Mitzenmacher
Abstract

Distributed Mean Estimation (DME) is a central building block in federated learning, where clients send local gradients to a parameter server for averaging and updating the model. Due to communication constraints, clients often use lossy compression techniques to compress the gradients, resulting in estimation inaccuracies.

DME is more challenging when clients have diverse network conditions, such as constrained communication budgets and packet losses. In such settings, DME techniques often incur a significant increase in the estimation error leading to degraded learning performance.

In this work, we propose a robust DME technique named EDEN that naturally handles heterogeneous communication budgets and packet losses. We derive appealing theoretical guarantees for EDEN and evaluate it empirically. Our results demonstrate that EDEN consistently improves over state-of-the-art DME techniques.

Distributed Mean Estimation, Federated Learning, Gradient Compression, Communication Efficiency.

1 Introduction

In the Distributed Mean Estimation (DME) problem, each of nğ‘›n senders has a dğ‘‘d-dimensional vector of real numbers. Each sender sends information over the network to a central receiver, who uses this information to estimate the mean of these vectors. This problem is a central building block in many federated learning scenarios, where at each training round, a parameter server averages clientsâ€™ parameter updates (i.e., neural network gradients) and updates its modelÂ (McMahan etÂ al., 2017). As neural network gradients are often large (e.g., can exceed a billion dimensionsÂ (Dean etÂ al., 2012; Shoeybi etÂ al., 2019; Huang etÂ al., 2019)), transmission over the network is often a bottleneck, and thus applying lossy compression to the gradients can be essential to adhere to client communication constraints, reduce the training time, and allow better inclusion and scalability.

Typically, the desired design property is that the receiverâ€™s resulting estimate will be unbiased. That is, the receiverâ€™s derived estimate x^^ğ‘¥\hat{x} for a senderâ€™s vector xâˆˆâ„dğ‘¥superscriptâ„ğ‘‘x\in\mathbb{R}^{d} should satisfy ğ”¼â€‹[x^]=xğ”¼delimited-[]^ğ‘¥ğ‘¥\mathbb{E}[\hat{x}]=x. Unbiasedness is attractive because, under natural conditions (including independence of estimates), as it yields a Mean Squared Error (MSE) between the mean of the received estimates and the mean of the true vectors that decays linearly with respect to the number of clients (e.g., see Vargaftik etÂ al. (2021)). Besides being a useful property for DME in isolation, in federated learning contexts this can remove the need for error feedback mechanisms that are commonly used to deal with biased estimatesÂ (Seide etÂ al., 2014; Karimireddy etÂ al., 2019), but are often not practical due to client participation patternsÂ (Kairouz etÂ al., 2021).

For unbiasedness, modern DME techniques employ randomized rounding techniques, commonly known as stochastic quantization (SQ), to map each vector coordinate to one of a limited number of possibilities, yielding a compressed form.

Some SQ-based techniques have known issues when used in DME. In particular, the resulting error is sensitive to the vectorâ€™s distribution and the difference between the largest and smallest coordinates. This is specifically problematic in federated learning, where neural network gradientsâ€™ coordinates can differ by orders of magnitude, rendering vanilla SQ inapplicable for accurate DME in many settings.

To address this limitation, recent works suggest the vector be randomly rotated prior to stochastic quantizationÂ (Suresh etÂ al., 2017). That is, the clients and the parameter server draw rotation matrices according to some known distribution (e.g., uniform); the clients then send the quantization of the rotated vectors while the parameter server applies the inverse rotation on the estimated rotated vector. Intuitively, the coordinates of a vector rotated by uniform random rotation are identically distributed (albeit weakly dependent) and are closely concentrated around their mean, leading to a small expected difference between the coordinates that allows for an accurate quantization. For xâˆˆâ„dğ‘¥superscriptâ„ğ‘‘x\in\mathbb{R}^{d}, this approach achieves a Normalized ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{MSE} (ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE})111The normalized ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{MSE} is the meanâ€™s estimate ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{MSE} normalized by the mean clientsâ€™ gradient squared norms (Â§2.1). of Oâ€‹(logâ¡dn)ğ‘‚ğ‘‘ğ‘›O(\frac{\log d}{n}) using Oâ€‹(1)ğ‘‚1O(1) bits per coordinate per client (i.e., Oâ€‹(nâ€‹d)ğ‘‚ğ‘›ğ‘‘O(nd) bits in total).

Another approach makes use of Kashinâ€™s representationÂ (Lyubarskii & Vershynin, 2010; Caldas etÂ al., 2018b; Safaryan etÂ al., 2020). Roughly speaking, it allows representing a dğ‘‘d-dimensional vector using larger vectors with Î»â‹…dâ‹…ğœ†ğ‘‘\lambda\cdot d coefficients for someÂ Î»>1ğœ†1\lambda>1, where each coefficient is smaller. Applying stochastic quantization to the Kashin coefficients allows anğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\,\mathit{NMSE} of Oâ€‹(1n)ğ‘‚1ğ‘›O(\frac{1}{n}) using Oâ€‹(Î»)ğ‘‚ğœ†O(\lambda) bits per coordinate. Compared withÂ (Suresh etÂ al., 2017), using Kashinâ€™s representation yields a lowerğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\,\mathit{NMSE} at the cost of increased computational complexityÂ (Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021).

Recent works propose algorithms that rely on clientsâ€™ gradient similarity to improve guarantees. For example,Â (Davies etÂ al., 2021) suggests an algorithm where if all clientsâ€™ gradients have pairwise Euclidean distances of at most aâˆˆâ„ğ‘â„a\in\mathbb{R}, the resultingğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\,\mathit{NMSE} is Oâ€‹(a2)ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘2O(a^{2}) using Oâ€‹(1)ğ‘‚1O(1) bits per coordinate on average. This solution provides a good bound when gradients are similar (and thus ağ‘a is small). However, it may be less efficient for federated learning, where clients often have different data distributions (and thus ağ‘a may be large).

The recently introduced DRIVEÂ (Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021) is a state-of-the-art DME algorithm that uses a single bit per coordinate. Formally, DRIVE offers anğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\,\mathit{NMSE} of Oâ€‹(1n)ğ‘‚1ğ‘›O\left(\frac{1}{n}\right) using (1+oâ€‹(1))1ğ‘œ1(1+o(1)) bits per coordinate and improves over existing DME techniques utilizing a similar communication budget both analytically and empirically. DRIVEâ€™s improvement stems from employing a deterministic quantization instead of a stochastic one after a random rotation, yielding an asymptoticğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\,\mathit{NMSE} improvement. DRIVE still produces unbiased estimates by adequately scaling the gradients.

A communication budget of one bit per coordinate has been thoroughly studiedÂ (Seide etÂ al., 2014; Wen etÂ al., 2017; Bernstein etÂ al., 2018; Karimireddy etÂ al., 2019; Ben-Basat etÂ al., 2021; Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021), and used to accelerate distributed learning systemsÂ (Jiang etÂ al., 2020; Bai etÂ al., 2021). However, one bit per coordinate does not support many federated learning scenarios where clients have different communication budgets and network conditions. We expand on alternative compression approaches, which are not directly applicable to DME, in AppendixÂ A.

In this work, we propose Efficient DME for diverse Networks (EDEN) â€“ a robust DME technique that supports heterogeneous communication budgets and packet loss rates. EDEN achieves anğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\,\mathit{NMSE} of Oâ€‹(1n)ğ‘‚1ğ‘›O\left(\frac{1}{n}\right) using bğ‘b bits per coordinate, for any constant bğ‘b, including for b<1ğ‘1b<1, i.e., less than one bit per coordinate. An additional feature of EDEN is that it naturally handles packet loss without retransmission by replacing lost coordinates with 0 values. We extend our theoretical results to this setting for constant packet loss rates and empirically demonstrate this robustness.

EDEN achieves improved accuracy using a novel formalization of the quantization framework. While previous work defines the quantization via a set of quantization points, our solution requires choosing a set of intervals whose union covers the real interval. Then, each point is quantized to the center of mass of its interval and not to the closest quantization point, which is counter-intuitive. That is, our solution may quantize some points to quantization levels farther away from them than the closest. Nonetheless, such a method can reduce the entropy of the quantized vector, allowing for better ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} given a communication budget.

We implement and evaluate EDEN in PyTorchÂ (Paszke etÂ al., 2019) and TensorFlowÂ (Abadi etÂ al., 2015)222Our PyTorch and TensorFlow implementations are available as open source at https://github.com/amitport/EDEN-Distributed-Mean-Estimation. and show that EDEN can compress vectors with more than 676767 million coordinates within 61Â ms. Compared with state-of-the-art DME techniques, EDEN consistently provides better mean estimation, which translates to higher accuracy in various federated and distributed learning tasks and scenarios.

2 EDEN

We start with preliminaries, overview EDEN, and then describe the complete details and guarantees.

2.1 Preliminaries

We assume that each sender has access to randomness that is shared with the central receiver. This assumption is standard (e.g.,Â Suresh etÂ al. (2017); Ben-Basat etÂ al. (2021); Vargaftik etÂ al. (2021)) and can be implemented by having a shared seed for a PseudoRandom Number Generator (PRNG). Importantly, each sender uses a different seed and thus its shared randomness is independent of that of other senders.

Formally, we are interested in efficiently solving the DME problem. In this problem, we have a set of nâˆˆâ„•+ğ‘›superscriptâ„•n\in\mathbb{N}^{+} senders and a central receiver. Further, in ML applications, zero gradients essentially never occur in practice. and sends a message to the receiver. The receiver then produces an estimate of the average of these sender vectors. In particular, we focus on the setting where each sender message yields an estimate of each senderâ€™s vector x^csubscript^ğ‘¥ğ‘\widehat{x}_{c}, and the receiver computes the average of the x^csubscript^ğ‘¥ğ‘\widehat{x}_{c} as an estimate of the average of the xcsubscriptğ‘¥ğ‘x_{c}, with the goal of minimizing itsğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\,\mathit{NMSE} defined as,

In federated learning and other techniques based on stochastic gradient descent (SGD) and its variants (e.g., McMahan etÂ al. (2017); Li etÂ al. (2020); Karimireddy etÂ al. (2020)), each round includes a mean estimation of the local vectors. Indeed, the ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} affects the convergence rate and often the final accuracy of the models. Further, the provable convex convergence rates for compressed SGD have a linear dependence on the ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE}Â (Bubeck (2015), TheoremÂ 6.3).

Deterministic Quantization. To encode a real-valued gradient using a finite number of bits, one must quantize it. To design the quantization, we leverage the fact that after randomly rotating a vector, all its coordinates are identically distributed. This distribution quickly converges to a normal distribution with the vectorâ€™s dimension. Specifically, for a vector xâˆˆâ„dğ‘¥superscriptâ„ğ‘‘x\in\mathbb{R}^{d}, we have that as dğ‘‘d tends to infinity, the distribution of each â„›â€‹(x)â„›ğ‘¥\mathcal{R}(x)â€™s coordinate tends to a normal distribution ğ’©â€‹(0,âˆ¥xâˆ¥22d)ğ’©0superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥22ğ‘‘\mathcal{N}(0,\frac{\left\lVert x\right\rVert_{2}^{2}}{d})Â (Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021).

EDEN also supports network packet losses without the need for retransmitting the lost coordinates (detailed in Â§4).

2.3 EDENâ€™s Scale

An appealing property of EDEN we establish in this work is that each sender can efficiently calculate the scale Scsubscriptğ‘†ğ‘S_{c} to make its estimate unbiased even though it uses a biased quantization technique. In particular, each sender cğ‘c uses:

Sc=âˆ¥xcâˆ¥22âŸ¨â„›câ€‹(xc),ğ’¬â€‹(Î·xcâ‹…â„›câ€‹(xc))âŸ©.subscriptğ‘†ğ‘superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘22subscriptâ„›ğ‘subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘ğ’¬â‹…subscriptğœ‚subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘subscriptâ„›ğ‘subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘S_{c}=\frac{\left\lVert x_{c}\right\rVert_{2}^{2}}{\left\langle\mathcal{R}_{c}(x_{c}),\mathcal{Q}(\eta_{x_{c}}\cdot\mathcal{R}_{c}(x_{c}))\right\rangle}~{}.

With this scale, we obtain the following formal guarantee whose proof appears in AppendixÂ B.

Theorem 2.1.

For all xâˆˆâ„dğ‘¥superscriptâ„ğ‘‘x\in\mathbb{R}^{d}, using EDEN with the scale S=âˆ¥xâˆ¥22âŸ¨â„›â€‹(x),ğ’¬â€‹(Î·xâ‹…â„›â€‹(x))âŸ©ğ‘†superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥22â„›ğ‘¥ğ’¬â‹…subscriptğœ‚ğ‘¥â„›ğ‘¥S=\frac{\left\lVert x\right\rVert_{2}^{2}}{\left\langle\mathcal{R}(x),\mathcal{Q}(\eta_{x}\cdot\mathcal{R}(x))\right\rangle} results in ğ”¼â€‹[x^]=xğ”¼delimited-[]^ğ‘¥ğ‘¥\mathbb{E}[\widehat{x}]=xÂ .

Intuitively, this scale ensures that the reconstructed vector x^csubscript^ğ‘¥ğ‘\widehat{x}_{c} lies on a hyperplane tangent to the original vectorâ€™s xcsubscriptğ‘¥ğ‘x_{c} point on the sphere. Since the rotation has no preferred direction, the expected value of the reconstructed vector produces precisely the original one. Specifically, the proof relies on this property by showing that for each rotation, there exists a matching rotation with the same bias but the opposite sign, and each such pairâ€™s average yields the original vector.

2.4 EDENâ€™sğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\,\mathit{NMSE}

Now, since the estimates of the sender vectors are independent (as senders sample their rotation matrices independently) and unbiased (according to TheoremÂ 2.1), we obtain the following result whose proof appears in AppendixÂ C.

Lemma 2.2.

Consider nğ‘›n senders. It holds that

ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸=âˆ‘c=1nğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸â€‹(c)â‹…âˆ¥xcâˆ¥22nâ‹…âˆ‘c=1nâˆ¥xcâˆ¥22.ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸superscriptsubscriptğ‘1ğ‘›â‹…ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘22â‹…ğ‘›superscriptsubscriptğ‘1ğ‘›superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘22\mathit{NMSE}=\frac{\sum_{c=1}^{n}\mathit{vNMSE}(c)\cdot\left\lVert x_{c}\right\rVert_{2}^{2}}{n\cdot\sum_{c=1}^{n}\left\lVert x_{c}\right\rVert_{2}^{2}}~{}.

3 Optimal 2bsuperscript2ğ‘2^{b}-Values Quantization

With bğ‘b bits per coordinate, we can use 2bsuperscript2ğ‘2^{b} quantization values. 4 Handling Heterogenity and Loss

We next detail how EDEN operates with general bit budget constraints and lossy networks, and discuss its compatibility with variable-length encoding techniques.

4.1 Heterogeneous Sender Bit Budget

Often in federated learning, senders may have different resource constraints, particularly networking constraintsÂ (Nishio & Yonetani, 2019). Therefore, it is beneficial for an algorithm to allow senders to use different amounts of compression, tuned to their own available communication budget. Accordingly, we provide two generalizations that maintain the strong guarantees of Theorems 2.1 and 2.3 and allow EDENâ€™s senders to adapt their bit budget per coordinate. Specifically, we allow each sender to use its own set of quantization values and to use a non-integer number of bits bğ‘b per coordinate (in expectation).

Super-bit compression (bâ‰¥1ğ‘1b\geq 1). For a sender who wishes to use an integer bğ‘b bits per coordinate, we simply use Qâ„bsubscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„ğ‘Q_{\mathcal{I}_{b}}. For non-integer b>1ğ‘1b>1, we propose the following generalization. We quantize each coordinate using Qâ„âŒŠbâŒ‹+1subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„ğ‘1Q_{\mathcal{I}_{\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor+1}} with probability bâˆ’âŒŠbâŒ‹ğ‘ğ‘b-\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor, and with Qâ„âŒŠbâŒ‹subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„ğ‘Q_{\mathcal{I}_{\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor}} with probability 1âˆ’(bâˆ’âŒŠbâŒ‹)1ğ‘ğ‘1-(b-\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor). This means that each clientâ€™s quantization is a distribution over Qâ„âŒŠbâŒ‹+1subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„ğ‘1Q_{\mathcal{I}_{\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor+1}} and Qâ„âŒŠbâŒ‹subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„ğ‘Q_{\mathcal{I}_{\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor}}. The choice of which coordinates to send using more bits are selected using shared randomness (to simulate independent weighted coin flips). In practice, this means the actual bit usage may slightly deviate from (but is concentrated around) its expected value of bğ‘b. This approach avoids introducing additional overhead from needing to communicate this information explicitly (although bğ‘b does need to be sent or otherwise agreed upon). We observe that Theorems 2.1 and 2.3 hold for this scenario (the proofs are in Appendix B and D respectively).

For example, for b=1.5ğ‘1.5b=1.5, each coordinate is quantized using Qâ„1subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„1Q_{\mathcal{I}_{1}} or Qâ„2subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„2Q_{\mathcal{I}_{2}} with equal probability. The resulting ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} for this case is (for dâ†’âˆâ†’ğ‘‘d\to\infty):

112â‹…ğ”¼â€‹[(ğ’¬â„1â€‹(z))2]+12â‹…ğ”¼â€‹[(ğ’¬â„2â€‹(z))2]âˆ’11â‹…12ğ”¼delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptğ’¬subscriptâ„1ğ‘§2â‹…12ğ”¼delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptğ’¬subscriptâ„2ğ‘§21\displaystyle\frac{1}{\frac{1}{2}\cdot\mathbb{E}\big{[}\left({\mathcal{Q}}_{\mathcal{I}_{1}}(z)\right)^{2}\big{]}+\frac{1}{2}\cdot\mathbb{E}\big{[}\left({\mathcal{Q}}_{\mathcal{I}_{2}}(z)\right)^{2}\big{]}}-1
â‰ˆ112â‹…(2Ï€)+12â‹…(0.88228)âˆ’1â‰ˆ0.317.absent1â‹…122ğœ‹â‹…120.8822810.317\displaystyle\approx\frac{1}{\frac{1}{2}\cdot(\frac{2}{\pi})+\frac{1}{2}\cdot(0.88228)}-1\approx 0.317.

We note that the naive solution of simply dividing the vector into two halves and sending each separately (one half using EDEN with Qâ„1subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„1Q_{\mathcal{I}_{1}} and the other with Qâ„2subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„2Q_{\mathcal{I}_{2}}) yields a higher ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} for the reconstructed vector (i.e., 12â‹…0.571+12â‹…0.134=0.352â‹…120.571â‹…120.1340.352\frac{1}{2}\cdot 0.571+\frac{1}{2}\cdot 0.134=0.352 instead of 0.3170.3170.317).

Sub-bit compression (b<1ğ‘1b<1). For sub-bit compression, we use Qâ„1subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„1Q_{\mathcal{I}_{1}} with random sparsification. Formally, the random sparsification procedure has only a single parameter pâˆˆ(0,1]ğ‘01p\in(0,1]. For a vector xâˆˆâ„dğ‘¥superscriptâ„ğ‘‘x\in\mathbb{R}^{d}, its random sparsification is 1pâ‹…mrâ€‹sâˆ˜xâ‹…1ğ‘subscriptğ‘šğ‘Ÿğ‘ ğ‘¥\frac{1}{p}\cdot m_{rs}\circ x, where mrâ€‹sâˆˆ{0,1}dsubscriptğ‘šğ‘Ÿğ‘ superscript01ğ‘‘m_{rs}\in\{0,1\}^{d} is a uniformly random sample of size âˆ¥mrâ€‹sâˆ¥1=dâ‹…psubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥subscriptğ‘šğ‘Ÿğ‘ 1â‹…ğ‘‘ğ‘\left\lVert m_{rs}\right\rVert_{1}=d\cdot p and âˆ˜\circ stands for the coordinate-wise product (i.e., mrâ€‹ssubscriptğ‘šğ‘Ÿğ‘ m_{rs} is a random mask). For random sparsification, it holds that

ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸=âˆ‘i=1d(1âˆ’p)â€‹xâ€‹[i]2+pâ€‹(1pâˆ’1)2â€‹xâ€‹[i]2âˆ¥xâˆ¥22=1pâˆ’1.ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘‘1ğ‘ğ‘¥superscriptdelimited-[]ğ‘–2ğ‘superscript1ğ‘12ğ‘¥superscriptdelimited-[]ğ‘–2superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥221ğ‘1\mathit{vNMSE}=\frac{{\sum_{i=1}^{d}(1-p)x[i]^{2}+p(\frac{1}{p}-1)^{2}x[i]^{2}}}{\left\lVert x\right\rVert_{2}^{2}}=\frac{1}{p}-1~{}.\vspace*{-1mm}

There are two ways to apply the random sparsification: before or after the rotation. In practice, we find that the resulting ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} is similar in both cases and use the sparsification prior to rotation which is more efficient since it reduces the dimension of the compressed vector.

For example, for b=0.7ğ‘0.7b=0.7, we sparsify uniformly at random 303030% of the coordinates (i.e., set p=0.7ğ‘0.7p=0.7), multiply the remaining coordinates by a factor of 10.710.7\frac{1}{0.7} to preserve unbiasedness, and then compress them using EDEN with Qâ„1subscriptğ‘„subscriptâ„1Q_{\mathcal{I}_{1}} (i.e., a single bit per coordinate). In turn, the receiver decodes the compressed sparsified vector and then restores the original using the same random mask (i.e., generating the same random mask using the shared randomness).

We strengthen the above choice using the following formal result whose proof appears in AppendixÂ E.

Lemma 4.1.

4.2 Lossy Networks

Distributed and federated learning systems (e.g.,Â Bai etÂ al. (2021); Jiang etÂ al. (2020)) typically assume reliable packet delivery, e.g., using TCP to retransmit lost packets or using RDMA or RoCEv2, which rely on a lossless fabric. However, it is useful to design algorithms that can cope with packet loss on standard IP networks. Indeed, a recent effort byÂ Ye etÂ al. (2021) extends SGD to support packet loss.

We model packet loss as a sparsification with parameter pâˆˆ(0,1]ğ‘01p\in(0,1], so a fraction pğ‘p of the coordinates arrive at the receiver. Hence this modeling is similar to that of the sub-bit regime, but there are inherent differences: (1) The sparsification may not be random. Instead, we assume an oblivious adversary may pick any subset of packets to drop. That is, the adversary may choose to drop packets based only on the packet indices, without any knowledge about the content of the packets; (2) The sparsification is done after the rotation; (3) The quantization scheme is not restricted to using â„1subscriptâ„1{\mathcal{I}_{1}}.

To support this scheme, no changes at the sender are required. For the receiver, before employing the inverse rotation and scaling, it simply treats any lost coordinates as 00 and multiplies the reconstructed rotated vector by 1p1ğ‘\frac{1}{p} (the receiver determines pğ‘p by counting the number of received coordinates). This scheme preserves our theoretical guarantees due to the following Lemma, which is proven in AppendixÂ F.

Lemma 4.3.

Let xâˆˆâ„dğ‘¥superscriptâ„ğ‘‘x\in\mathbb{R}^{d} and let mdâ€‹sâˆˆ{0,1}dsubscriptğ‘šğ‘‘ğ‘ superscript01ğ‘‘m_{ds}\in\{0,1\}^{d} be a deterministic mask. Denote p=âˆ¥mdâ€‹sâˆ¥1dğ‘subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥subscriptğ‘šğ‘‘ğ‘ 1ğ‘‘p=\frac{\left\lVert m_{ds}\right\rVert_{1}}{d} and let â„›dâ€‹sâ€‹(x)=1pâ‹…mdâ€‹sâˆ˜â„›â€‹(x)subscriptâ„›ğ‘‘ğ‘ ğ‘¥â‹…1ğ‘subscriptğ‘šğ‘‘ğ‘ â„›ğ‘¥\mathcal{R}_{ds}(x)=\frac{1}{p}\cdot m_{ds}\circ\mathcal{R}(x). Then, using EDEN with â„›dâ€‹sâ€‹(x)subscriptâ„›ğ‘‘ğ‘ ğ‘¥\mathcal{R}_{ds}(x) instead of â„›â€‹(x)â„›ğ‘¥\mathcal{R}(x) results in:

  1. 1.

    ğ”¼â€‹[x^]=xğ”¼delimited-[]^ğ‘¥ğ‘¥\mathbb{E}\left[\widehat{x}\right]=xÂ .

  2. 2.

    ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸â‰¤1pâ‹…ğ”¼â€‹[(ğ’¬â€‹(z))2]âˆ’1+Oâ€‹(logâ¡ddâ‹…p2)ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸1â‹…ğ‘ğ”¼delimited-[]superscriptğ’¬ğ‘§21ğ‘‚ğ‘‘â‹…ğ‘‘superscriptğ‘2\mathit{vNMSE}\leq\frac{1}{p\cdot\mathbb{E}\left[\left({\mathcal{Q}}(z)\right)^{2}\right]}-1+O\left(\sqrt{\frac{\log d}{d\cdot p^{2}}}\right)Â .

LemmaÂ 4.3 shows that when performing DME, we can settle for partial information from all the senders and can replace missing information by 0s and rescale each vector accordingly. Of course, this increases the error, but LemmaÂ 4.3 bounds this increase. This feature enables the use of lossy transport protocols such as UDP (e.g., as proposed byÂ Ye etÂ al. (2021)), or allows the receiver to avoid waiting for retransmissions of lost packets. Hence we can trade-off error and delay (latency) by allowing partial information. Another benefit is that lossy protocols often have reduced overheads (e.g., smaller headers) since they do not require maintaining state and reliable delivery.

4.3 Variable-Length Encoding

A standard approach to compressing vectors with a small number of possible values that are unequally distributed is using entropy encoding methods such as HuffmanÂ (Huffman, 1952) or arithmetic encodingÂ (Pasco, 1976; Rissanen, 1976). Intuitively, the number of times each quantization value appears in ğ’¬â€‹(Î·xâ‹…â„›â€‹(x))ğ’¬â‹…subscriptğœ‚ğ‘¥â„›ğ‘¥\mathcal{Q}(\eta_{x}\cdot\mathcal{R}(x)) may not be d|â„|ğ‘‘â„\frac{d}{|\mathcal{I}|}. Indeed, for â„bsubscriptâ„ğ‘\mathcal{I}_{b} with bâ‰¥2ğ‘2b\geq 2, the probability of the values is not equal.

Formally, denoting by pI=â„™â€‹(zâˆˆI)subscriptğ‘ğ¼â„™ğ‘§ğ¼p_{I}=\mathbbm{P}(z\in I) the probability that a normal variable zâˆˆğ’©â€‹(0,1)ğ‘§ğ’©01z\in\mathcal{N}(0,1) lies in the interval Iğ¼I, Hâ„â‰œâˆ‘Iâˆˆâ„âˆ’pIâ€‹log2â¡(pI)â‰œsubscriptğ»â„subscriptğ¼â„subscriptğ‘ğ¼subscript2subscriptğ‘ğ¼H_{\mathcal{I}}\triangleq\sum_{I\in\mathcal{I}}-p_{I}\log_{2}(p_{I}) is the entropy of the distribution induced by â„â„\mathcal{I}. For example, as discussed in ExampleÂ 2 (Â§3), for â„2subscriptâ„2\mathcal{I}_{2}, the intervals [âˆ’0.9816,0],[0,0.9816]0.9816000.9816[-0.9816,0],[0,0.9816] have probability that is more than double than that of (âˆ’âˆ,0.9816],[0.9816,âˆ)0.98160.9816(-\infty,0.9816],[0.9816,\infty). The entropy of the distribution is Hâ„2â‰ˆ1.91subscriptğ»subscriptâ„21.91H_{\mathcal{I}_{2}}\approx 1.91 bits. This suggests that, for a large enough dimension dğ‘‘d, we should be able to compress the vector to at most Hâ„2+Ïµsubscriptğ»subscriptâ„2italic-ÏµH_{\mathcal{I}_{2}}+\epsilon bits per coordinate for any constant Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon.

Such an encoding may also allow us to use more quantization values for the same bit budget. For example, using the Lloyd-Max Scalar QuantizerÂ (Lloyd, 1982; Max, 1960) with 999 quantization values, we get an entropy of â‰ˆ2.98absent2.98\approx 2.98 bits, which would allow us to use three bits per coordinate for large enough vectors. In particular, this would reduce the ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} by nearly 20%, compared to â„3subscriptâ„3\mathcal{I}_{3}, at the cost of additional computation.

Taking this a step further, it is possible to consider the resulting entropy when choosing the set of intervals. To optimize the quantization, we are looking for a set â„â„\mathcal{I} that maximizes ğ”¼â€‹[(ğ’¬â„â€‹(z))2]ğ”¼delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptğ’¬â„ğ‘§2{\mathbb{E}\left[{\left(\mathcal{Q}_{\mathcal{I}}(z)\right)}^{2}\right]} such that its entropy is bounded by bğ‘b. This problem is called Entropy-Constrained Vector Quantization (ECVQ)Â (Chou etÂ al., 1989). The algorithm proposed inÂ Chou etÂ al. (1989) has several tunable parameters that may affect the output of the algorithm. We implemented the algorithm and scanned a large variety of parameter values. For b=3ğ‘3b=3, for example, the best obtained ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} is â‰ˆ0.02274absent0.02274\approx 0.02274, compared to an ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} of â‰ˆ0.03572absent0.03572\approx 0.03572 for EDEN with â„3subscriptâ„3\mathcal{I}_{3} and without entropy encoding.

We propose a simpler approach that is more computationally efficient. 5 Evaluation

We evaluate EDEN using different federated and distributed learning tasks. We compare with a non-compressed baseline that uses 32-bit floating-point representation for each coordinate (Float32) and the following DME techniques: (1) Stochastic quantization (SQ) applied after the randomized Hadamard transform (Hadamard + SQ)Â (Suresh etÂ al., 2017; KoneÄná»³ & RichtÃ¡rik, 2018)666SQÂ (Barnes etÂ al., 1951; Connolly etÂ al., 2021) normalizes the vector into the range [0,2bâˆ’1]0superscript2ğ‘1[0,2^{b}-1] (using min-max normalization), adds uniform noise in (âˆ’0.5,0.5)0.50.5(-0.5,0.5), and then rounds to the nearest integer. thus providing an unbiased estimate of each coordinate.; (2) SQ applied over the vectorâ€™s Kashinâ€™s representation (Kashin + SQ)Â Â (Lyubarskii & Vershynin, 2010; Caldas etÂ al., 2018b; Safaryan etÂ al., 2020); and (3) QSGD (Alistarh etÂ al., 2017), which normalizes the input vector by its euclidean norm and separately sends its sign and its quantized (using SQ) absolute values.

We exclude methods that involve client-side memory since these can often work in conjunction with all tested methods (e.g.,Â Karimireddy etÂ al. (2019); RichtÃ¡rik etÂ al. (2021)) and are less applicable in cross-device federated scenariosÂ (Kairouz etÂ al., 2021). Also, we omit DRIVEÂ (Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021) since its performance is identical to that of EDEN with â„1subscriptâ„1\mathcal{I}_{1} and no packet losses.

Unless otherwise noted, we evaluate the algorithms without variable-length encoding which increases encoding time. We compare with SQGD + Elias Omega encodingÂ (Alistarh etÂ al., 2017) and optimized stochastic quantization + HuffmanÂ (Suresh etÂ al., 2017) in AppendixÂ G.1.

Similarly to Hadamard + SQ, Kashin + SQ, and DRIVE, instead of using a uniform random rotation (which requires Oâ€‹(d3)ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘‘3O(d^{3}) time and Oâ€‹(d2)ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘‘2O(d^{2}) space) to rotate the vector, we use the randomized Hadamard transform (a.k.a. structured random rotationÂ (Suresh etÂ al., 2017; Ailon & Chazelle, 2009)) that admits a fast, in-place, parallelizable, and GPU-friendly, Oâ€‹(dâ€‹logâ¡d)ğ‘‚ğ‘‘ğ‘‘O(d\log d) time implementationÂ (Fino & Algazi, 1976; Li etÂ al., 2018; Ailon & Chazelle, 2009). As with these prior works, we find essentially negligible difference in our evaluation between using the Hadamard rotations and fully random rotations. We discuss this further and show supporting empirical measurements in AppendixÂ H.

5.1 Implementation Optimization

In a natural implementation, EDEN has additional complexity when using bâ‰ 1ğ‘1b\neq 1 bits per coordinate. Indeed, for b<1ğ‘1b<1, we need to sample the sparsification mask, and for b>1ğ‘1b>1, we need to identify the interval each rotated coordinate lies in and take its center of mass. The latter can be efficiently done using a binary search - e.g., torch.bucketize, leading to an encoding complexity of Oâ€‹(dâ‹…b)ğ‘‚â‹…ğ‘‘ğ‘O(d\cdot b)).

Instead, we implement EDEN using a fine-grained lookup table with a resulting encoding complexity of Oâ€‹(d)ğ‘‚ğ‘‘O(d) (i.e., independent of bğ‘b). That is, we map each value zğ‘§z to an integer nz=âŒŠzÎ³âŒ‹subscriptğ‘›ğ‘§ğ‘§ğ›¾n_{z}=\left\lfloor{\frac{z}{\gamma}}\right\rfloor for a suitably selected small value Î³ğ›¾\gamma, and our lookup table maps nzsubscriptğ‘›ğ‘§n_{z} to the message the sender sends. Similarly, we have a receiver lookup table that maps nzsubscriptğ‘›ğ‘§n_{z} to an estimated value. The choice of Î³ğ›¾\gamma provides a tradeoff between space and accuracy. We note that, even with tables whose size is small compared to the encoded vector (e.g., 0.1%), the tableâ€™s granularity is fine enough to get that the additional error is negligible (e.g., less than 0.01%) compared with the error of the algorithm. Further, it does not affect the unbiasedness of the algorithm, which is guaranteed by taking the correct scale (see TheoremÂ 2.1). This approach allows us to encode and decode coordinates with minimal computation, especially when variable length encoding is not used.

5.2 ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE}, ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE}, and Encoding Speed

We next evaluate the ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} and encoding speed of EDEN, comparing to three other DME techniques. In Figure 2, we provide representative results for a bit budget b=2,4,6ğ‘246b=2,4,6 for vectors that are drawn from a LogNormal(0,1) distribution. Each data point is averaged over 100 trials. EDEN offers the best ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} and is faster than Kashin + SQ, which offers the second lowest error. In line with theory, the ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} of Hadamard + SQ and the fast QSGD increases with the dimension. In all experiments, EDENâ€™s encoding time accounts to less than 1% of the computation of the gradient. AppendixÂ I.1 provides further experiments of ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} and encode speeds, all indicating similar trends.

5.3 Federated Learning

We evaluate EDEN over the federated versions of the EMNISTÂ (Cohen etÂ al., 2017) image classification task and the ShakespeareÂ (Shakespeare, ) next-word prediction task. We excluded QSGD, which was less competitive in these experiments. We run FedAvgÂ (McMahan etÂ al., 2017) with the Adam server optimizerÂ (Kingma & Ba, 2015) and sample n=10ğ‘›10n=10 clients per round. We re-use code, client partitioning, models, and hyperparameters from the federated learning benchmark of Reddi etÂ al. (2021). Those are restated for convenience in AppendixÂ I.2.

FigureÂ 3 shows how EDEN compares with other compression schemes at various bit budgets. We notice that EDEN considerably outperforms other methods at the lower bit regimes. At 4 bits, all methods converge near the baseline, while EDEN still maintains a relative advantage.

5.4 Additional Evaluation

Due to space limits, we defer additional evaluation results to the Appendix. In particular, we provide experiments for variable-length encoding (AppendixÂ G.1); structured rotation performance against the theory of uniform rotation (AppendixÂ H); ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸,ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE,vNMSE}, and encoding speed (AppendixÂ I.1); distributed logistic regression (AppendixÂ I.3); comparison of sub-bit compression and network loss (AppendixÂ I.4); distributed power iteration (AppendixÂ I.5); homogeneous federated learning (AppendixÂ I.6); and cross-device federated learning (AppendixÂ I.7).

To summarize these experiments, we show EDEN outperforms its competitors in nearly all cases, offering a combination of speed, accuracy, overall compression, and robustness, and we believe that this will make it the best choice for many applications.

6 Conclusions

In this paper, we presented EDEN, a robust and accurate distributed mean estimation technique. EDEN suits various network scenarios, including packet losses and heterogeneous clients. Further, we proved strong accuracy guarantees for a wide range of usage scenarios, including using entropy encoding to compress quantized vectors further and working over lossy networks while maintaining high precision. Our evaluation results indicate that EDEN considerably outperforms all tested techniques in nearly all settings.

As future work, we propose to study how to combine EDEN with techniques that provide fast receiver decode procedures, e.g., using a single rotation for all senders to avoid inverse rotating individual vectors. Another direction is to combine EDEN with techniques such as secure aggregation and differential privacy. It is also interesting to explore if EDEN can be adapted to all-reduce techniques, which benefit large-scale distributed deployments where a parameter server might be a bottleneck. Finally, while EDEN naturally extends to linear schemes such as weighted mean, we propose to study how to incorporate non-linear aggregation functions, such as approximate geometric median, that may improve the training robustnessÂ (Pillutla etÂ al., 2022).

Our source code is available at:
Â https://github.com/amitport/EDEN-Distributed-Mean-Estimation.

Appendix A Alternative Compression Methods

In this paper, we focus on the DME problem, in which the participants do not keep state, and the estimate of each vector is desired to be unbiased for the ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} to decrease linearly with respect to the number of senders. We give a few examples of other approaches (i.e., works that do not directly address the DME problem).

Some works (e.g.,Â Beznosikov etÂ al. (2020)) investigate the convergence rate of Stochastic Gradient Decent (SGD) for biased compression (which are known to achieve lower error). Another approach to leverage the lower error of biased compression is using Error Feedback (EF). Namely, if the senders are persistent (the same devices are used over multiple rounds) and have the memory to store the error of their compressed gradient, they can use this information to compensate for the estimation error between rounds. Indeed, works such asÂ Seide etÂ al. (2014); Alistarh etÂ al. (2018); RichtÃ¡rik etÂ al. (2021) show that EF-based approaches can greatly increase the accuracy of the learned models and ensure convergence of biased compressors such as Top-kğ‘˜k (Stich etÂ al., 2018) and SketchedSGDÂ (Ivkin etÂ al., 2019).

For a setting with persistent clients, recent works (e.g.,Â Mishchenko etÂ al. (2019); Gorbunov etÂ al. (2021)) also suggest encoding the difference between the current gradient and the one from the previous round. Intuitively, when the mini-batch sizes are sufficiently large, the sampled gradients are less noisy, and encoding the differences allows faster convergence. This approach is orthogonal to EDEN which can encode the difference in such a setting.

For distributed cluster learning, some works aim at optimizing streaming aggregation (i.e., All-Reduce operations) via programmable hardwareÂ (Sapio etÂ al., 2021) or taking advantage of data sparsityÂ (Fei etÂ al., 2021). These approaches are known to be orthogonal to (and can work in conjunction with) compression techniquesÂ (Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021; Fei etÂ al., 2021). For example, if the input is sparse (or is sparsified), one can use EDEN to encode only the non-zero coordinates.

Deep gradient compressionÂ (Lin etÂ al., 2018) leverages redundancy in neural network gradients to reduce the number of transmitted bits. They leverage momentum correction, local gradient clipping, momentum factor masking, and warm-up training, and report compression ratios of 270x-600x.

For further overview we refer the reader toÂ KoneÄnÃ½ etÂ al. (2017); Kairouz etÂ al. (2021); Wang etÂ al. (2021).

Appendix B EDENâ€™s Unbiasedness

For clarity, we restate the theorem.

See 2.1

Lemma D.4.

It holds that,

ğ”¼â€‹[âˆ¥xâˆ’â„¬â€‹(ğ’œâ€‹(x))âˆ¥22]âˆ¥xâˆ¥22ğ”¼delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥â„¬ğ’œğ‘¥22superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥22\displaystyle\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[\left\lVert x-\mathcal{B}(\mathcal{A}(x))\right\rVert_{2}^{2}\right]}{\left\lVert x\right\rVert_{2}^{2}} =ğ”¼â€‹[âˆ¥xâˆ’zâˆ¥22]âˆ¥xâˆ¥22=ğ”¼â€‹[âˆ¥xâˆ’yâˆ¥22]âˆ¥xâˆ¥22+ğ”¼â€‹[âˆ¥yâˆ’zâˆ¥22]âˆ¥xâˆ¥22absentğ”¼delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥ğ‘§22superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥22ğ”¼delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥ğ‘¦22superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥22ğ”¼delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¦ğ‘§22superscriptsubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğ‘¥22\displaystyle=\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[\left\lVert x-z\right\rVert_{2}^{2}\right]}{\left\lVert x\right\rVert_{2}^{2}}=\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[\left\lVert x-y\right\rVert_{2}^{2}\right]}{\left\lVert x\right\rVert_{2}^{2}}+\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[\left\lVert y-z\right\rVert_{2}^{2}\right]}{\left\lVert x\right\rVert_{2}^{2}}

Intuitively, the reason why unbiasedness is preserved with a deterministic mask is that all coordinates of the rotated and quantized vector follow the same distribution, and thus after the inverse rotation and scaling, the distribution of the reconstructed vector depends only on the number of zeros in the mask but not on their indices.

G.2 Variable-Length Encoding Representation Length

In practice, the frequency of a quantization value Iâˆˆâ„ğ¼â„I\in\mathcal{I} may not be exactly pIâ‹…dâ‹…subscriptğ‘ğ¼ğ‘‘p_{I}\cdot d. Nonetheless, using arithmetic-coding, we can get an encoding that uses (Hâ„+Ïµ)â€‹(1+oâ€‹(1))subscriptğ»â„italic-Ïµ1ğ‘œ1(H_{\mathcal{I}}+\epsilon)(1+o(1)) bits per coordinate on average. A proof sketch, which assumes that the coordinates are independent (in practice, they are weakly dependent for a sufficiently large dimension dğ‘‘d) follows. We defer the formal proof to future work. As indicated byÂ Mitzenmacher & Upfal (2017) (see Chapter 10), from the fact that each coordinate jğ‘—j of a vector yâˆˆâ„dğ‘¦superscriptâ„ğ‘‘y\in\mathbb{R}^{d}, decreases the length of the encoded interval by a factor of â„’ğ’¬â€‹(yâ€‹[j])subscriptâ„’ğ’¬ğ‘¦delimited-[]ğ‘—\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}(y[j])}, where â„’ğ’¬â€‹(yâ€‹[j])subscriptâ„’ğ’¬ğ‘¦delimited-[]ğ‘—\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}(y[j])} is the random variable that represents the quantization value of the interval of yâ€‹[j]ğ‘¦delimited-[]ğ‘—y[j]. Therefore, the length of the interval of the vector is â„’yâ‰œâˆj=0dâˆ’1â„’ğ’¬â€‹(yâ€‹[j])â‰œsubscriptâ„’ğ‘¦superscriptsubscriptproductğ‘—0ğ‘‘1subscriptâ„’ğ’¬ğ‘¦delimited-[]ğ‘—\mathcal{L}_{y}\triangleq\prod_{j=0}^{d-1}\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}(y[j])} which means that the representation of yğ‘¦y requires âŒˆlog2â¡(1â„’y)+1âŒ‰â‰¤2+âˆ‘j=0dâˆ’1log2â¡1â„’ğ’¬â€‹(yâ€‹[j])subscript21subscriptâ„’ğ‘¦12superscriptsubscriptğ‘—0ğ‘‘1subscript21subscriptâ„’ğ’¬ğ‘¦delimited-[]ğ‘—\left\lceil\log_{2}{(\frac{1}{\mathcal{L}_{y}})}+1\right\rceil\leq 2+\sum_{j=0}^{d-1}\log_{2}\frac{1}{\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}(y[j])}}. A standard application of the Chernoff bound suffices to complete the argument.

Appendix H Structured Rotation

To improve computational efficiency, the randomized Hadamard transform is used in different domains to replace computationally extensive matrix multiplications. This is now common. For example: in Â Rader (1969); Thomas (2013); Herendi etÂ al. (1997), it is used to develop a computationally cheap methods to generate independent normally distributed variables from simpler (e.g., uniform) distributions; in Yu etÂ al. (2016), it is used in the context of Gaussian kernel approximation, replacing the random Gaussian matrix; in Choromanski etÂ al. (2018), it is used for gradient estimation in derivative-free optimization reinforcement learning; in Choromanski etÂ al. (2017), it is used for efficient computation of embeddings.

In our context, it is used by recent DME techniques (Hadamard + SQÂ (Suresh etÂ al., 2017; KoneÄná»³ & RichtÃ¡rik, 2018), Kashin + SQÂ (Lyubarskii & Vershynin, 2010; Caldas etÂ al., 2018b; Safaryan etÂ al., 2020) and DRIVEÂ (Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021)). WhileÂ (Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021) pointed out an adversarial example for a single transform, we are not aware of adversarial inputs for more than a single transform. For some use cases, previous works (e.g.,Â Yu etÂ al. (2016); Andoni etÂ al. (2015)) suggest using 2-3 transforms to avert the dependency on the input. In the case of neural networks, as was indicated byÂ (Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021), when the input vector is high dimensional and admits finite moments, a single transform performs sufficiently similar to a uniform rotation. As recently reported by several works, this is indeed the case in common DNN workloads where gradients and network parameters follow, e.g., the lognormalÂ (Chmiel etÂ al., 2021) or normal (Banner etÂ al., 2019; Ye etÂ al., 2020) distributions.

In FigureÂ 6, we show how EDENâ€™s ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} with a single transform aligns with the theoretical bound (CorollaryÂ 2.4) for all tested input distributions (LogNormal, Normal, Exponential, Ï‡2superscriptğœ’2\chi^{2}, Half-Normal, Beta, and others not shown) and vector dimensions. As can be seen, even a single randomized Hadamard transform aligns extremely closely with the theoretical results for a uniform random rotation, so that one cannot visually distinguish the results. For even smaller dimensions (e.g., d=16ğ‘‘16d=16), we observed a slightly higher error for the implementation than the theoretical asymptotic bound, as the Oâ€‹(logâ¡dd)ğ‘‚ğ‘‘ğ‘‘O\left(\sqrt{\frac{\log d}{d}}\right) term of TheoremÂ 2.3 is not negligible. However, since our interest is in neural network gradients of large dimension, this is not important for this application.

Appendix I Additional Simulation Details and Results

I.1 ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE}, ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE}, and encoding speed

Here, we run the experiment of FigureÂ 2 with different bit budgets bğ‘b and depict the results in FigureÂ 7. As shown, EDEN has the lowest ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} for all dimension and bit budget combinations, and is also significantly faster than the second most accurate solution, Kashin + SQ. As in FigureÂ 2, the ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} of EDEN and Kashin + SQ is bounded independently of the dimension while Hadamard + SQâ€™s and QSGDâ€™s error increases with dğ‘‘d.

Our encoding speed measurements are performed using NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3090 GPU. The machine has Intel Core i9-10980XE CPU (18 cores, 3.00 GHz, and 24.75 MB cache) and 128 GB RAM. We use Ubuntu 20.04.2 LTS operating system, CUDA release 11.1 (V11.1.105), and PyTorch version 1.10.1.

Next, we conduct experiments with a vector of size d=11511784ğ‘‘11511784d=11511784 (the number of parameters in a ResNet18 architecture) in a DME setting where c=10ğ‘10c=10 senders send their vectors to a receiver for averaging. We test the different DME techniques over different distributions. Each data point is repeated 100 times and we report the mean and standard deviation. In addition, here we also compare against Count-SketchÂ (Charikar etÂ al., 2002), which is the main building block for some recent distributed and federated compression schemes (e.g.,Â Ivkin etÂ al. (2019)).

We sweep over a bit budget of 1-8 bits per coordinate. The results, shown in FigureÂ 8, indicate that: (1) as dictated by theory, EDENâ€™s ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} is not sensitive to the specific distribution; (2) EDEN significantly improves over all techniques for all bit budgets (notice the logarithmic ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} scale). Moreover, there is no consistent runner-up in this DME experiment since different competitors are more accurate for different distributions and bit budgets.

Several additional trends are evident: (1) Count-Sketch is competitive for a low communication budget but not for a higher ones. This is expected since its error guarantee decreases polynomially in bğ‘b (which linearly affects its number of counters). In contrast, for other techniques, the error decreases exponentially (i.e., doubling the number of quantization values for each added bit); (2) For most bit budgets, the most competitive DME algorithm to ours in terms of ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{NMSE} is Kashin + SQ. However, its accuracy is less prominent for high bit budgets constraints where its coefficient representation dominates the error (which can be improved with more iterations, at the cost of additional computation); (3) QSGD employs uniform quantization values and therefore performs better for light tailed distributions. For example, for the heavy-tailed Log-Normal distribution, which is common in machine learning workloads and, in particular, neural network gradients (e.g.,Â Chmiel etÂ al. (2021)), its performance degrades notably.

Finally, recall that for b=1ğ‘1b=1 and no coordinate losses, EDEN and DRIVEÂ (Vargaftik etÂ al., 2021) admit the same performance.

I.2 EMNIST and Shakespeare experiments details

The EMNIST and Shakespeare federated learning experiments, presented inÂ Â§5.3, follow precisely the setup described inÂ Reddi etÂ al. (2021) for the Adam server optimizer case, which we restate in TableÂ 1.

The client partitioning of these datasets was designed to naturally simulate a realistic heterogeneous federated learning setting. Specifically, federated EMNISTÂ (Caldas etÂ al., 2018a) includes 749,068 handwritten characters partitioned among their 3400 writers (i.e., this is the total number of clients), and federated ShakespeareÂ (McMahan etÂ al., 2017) consists of 18,424 lines of text from Shakespeare plays partitioned among the respective 715 speakers (i.e., clients). For EMNIST, a CNN with two convolutional layers is used (with â‰ˆ1.2â€‹Mabsent1.2ğ‘€{\approx}1.2M parameters), and for Shakespeare, a standard LSTM recurrent model (Hochreiter & Schmidhuber, 1997) (with â‰ˆ820â€‹Kabsent820ğ¾{\approx}820K parameters).

Additionally, for completeness, we include FigureÂ 9, which is a zoomed-out version of FigureÂ 3.

I.3 Distributed Logistic Regression

While the federated learning benchmarks demonstrate the applicability of our method, they are also often noisy and generally converge with low bit budgets. In contrast, logistic regression allows us to show more fine-grained differences between the methods for super-bit budgets. We perform an experiment similar to that of Malinovskiy etÂ al. (2020) (Â§4). In particular, we use UCIâ€™s Census Income binary prediction taskÂ (Kohavi etÂ al., 1996) with the discretization described inÂ (Platt, 1998)777Available at https://www.csie.ntu.edu.tw/~cjlin/libsvmtools/datasets/binary.html#a9a. and divide the data equally among 20 clients. With each compression strategy, we run distributed gradient descent where, in each round, clients report the full gradient over their share, and the server uses the average of these gradients to take a step towards the optimum. Given that this is a convex setup, we expect the lower variance unbiased gradient estimates to consistently move towards the optimum. We run each compression scheme for 100 rounds with different bit budgets and report the Euclidean distance of the model parameters from the model received without any compression. We present the results in FigureÂ 10. As hypothesized, EDEN is closer to the optimum than other methods in all the bit budgets we measured.

I.4 Loss vs. Sub-bit

We now measure the ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} under network loss and for sub-bit compression. Intuitively, while in both not all coordinates are received by the receiver, our sub-bit compression selects a uniform random mask of coordinates that are encoded while packet loss may be arbitrary (e.g., in blocks). A different view point is that sub-bit compression means sparsifying the vector prior to the random rotation while packet drops means loss of coordinates in the rotated vector. As shown in FigureÂ 11, the empirical ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} of the two is identical (when the same fraction of coordinates is received) and follows the theory of CorollaryÂ 4.2 and LemmaÂ 4.3. Indeed, as shown by LemmaÂ 4.1, the ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} equals A+Aâ€‹B+Bğ´ğ´ğµğµA+AB+B (where Ağ´A is EDENâ€™s ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸ğ‘£ğ‘ğ‘€ğ‘†ğ¸\mathit{vNMSE} and B is the sparsificationâ€™s) regardless of the orders in which ğ’œğ’œ\mathcal{A} and â„¬â„¬\mathcal{B} are applied.

I.5 Distributed Power Iteration

For some machine learning tasks (e.g., Principal Component Analysis), power iteration, which approximates the dominant eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a matrix, is used as a sub-routine. We perform an experiment with 101010 clients and a server that jointly compute the top eigenvector in a matrix that is distributed among the clients. In particular, the training occurs in rounds where in each training round we have the following sequence of events:

  • â€¢

    Each client updates the top eigenvector based on its local data, compresses it, and sends it to the server.

  • â€¢

    For each client, the server calculates the diff vector between the eigenvector from the previous round, averages the diffs and updates the eigenvector estimation using this average scaled by a learning rate of 0.1.

  • â€¢

    The server sends the updated eigenvector estimation to all of the clients.

For each compression scheme, we vary the bit budget bğ‘b from one bit to eight and measure the L2 norm of the diff between the final eigenvector to the optimal solution (i.e., the achieved eigenvector without compression). FigureÂ 12 presents the results for the MNIST and CIFAR-10Â (Krizhevsky, 2009; LeCun etÂ al., 1998, 2010) datasets. It is evident that in both datasets, EDEN achieves the lowest L2 error for all values of bğ‘b.

I.6 Homogeneous federated learning

We simulate two federated scenarios with 10 clients and the CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 datasetsÂ (Krizhevsky, 2009). For both scenarios the data is uniformly distributed among the clients. We use a batch size of 128, an SGD optimizer with a Cross entropy loss criterion, and each client performs a single training step at each round. For CIFAR-10, we use the ResNet-9Â (He etÂ al., 2016) architecture with learning rate of 0.1, and the bit budget bğ‘b is set to 0.1. For CIFAR-100, we use the ResNet-18Â (He etÂ al., 2016) architecture with learning rate of 0.05, and the bit budget bğ‘b is set to 0.5.

FigureÂ 13 presents the test and train accuracy of EDEN and competitive compression schemes, with a smoothing rolling mean window of 60 rounds. In both scenarios, EDEN achieves the highest accuracy. More specifically, for CIFAR-100, EDEN is the only compression scheme that converges for such a low bit budget.

I.7 Cross-device federated learning

We simulate two cross-device federated scenarios with 50 clients and the MNIST and CIFAR-10 datasetsÂ (Krizhevsky, 2009; LeCun etÂ al., 1998, 2010). For both scenarios, 10 clients are randomly chosen at each training round, and each client performs five local training steps. We use a batch size of 128, an SGD optimizer with a cross entropy loss criterion, and the bit budget bğ‘b is set to 0.05, testing a setting with very aggressive compression.

For MNIST, we use LeNet-5Â (LeCun etÂ al., 1998) with a learning rate of 0.05. To simulate severe heterogeneity, each client holds data instances that belong to a single class (i.e., severe label skew). For the CIFAR-10 configuration, we use ResNet-9Â (He etÂ al., 2016) with a learning rate of 0.1, and the data is uniformly distributed among the clients.

FigureÂ 14 presents the test and train accuracy of EDEN and the competitive compression schemes, with a smoothing rolling mean window of 30 rounds. In both scenarios, EDEN achieves the highest accuracy. For MNIST, EDEN is only slightly below the baseline model (without compression).
